  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of health services to drought affected population in Sar-e-Pul, Samangan and Helmand provinces</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project will focus on addressing the health needs of the population in Sar-e-Pul, Samangan and Helmand provinces to drought affected population without overlapping with the already Basic Package of Health Services (BPHS) activities. The project interventions have been designed for six months targeting a total 10 districts in three provinces (Gosfandi, Sancharak, Sar-e-Pul and Sozma Qala in Sar-e-Pul, Feroz Nakhshir and Hazrat -e- Sultan in Samangan and Deh Sahu, Nadali, Nawzad and Reg districts of Hilmand). The project activities are aligned with the 3rd Reserved Allocation 2018 strategy and effectively address the health cluster priorities which aim at reducing the mortality and morbidity chiefly due to drought. The fact that ORCD has already received a grant through nutrition cluster for the provision of nutrition services to drought affected population in Sar-e-Pul by already establishing two mobile health  teams, health services provision through the proposed 4 mobile health teams in this province will be integrated with nutrition service delivery

ORCD will establish a total 8 mobile health teams targeting a total 10 districts in two provinces (4 mobile health teams in 4 districts of Sar-e-Pul, 2 mobile health teams in 2 priority districts of Samangan and 4 districts of Hilmand). These mobile health teams will provide basic primary health care as per the BPHS in line with the Ministry of Public Health (MoPH) Mobile Health Package of Health Services (MPHS) for a period of 6 months chiefly targeting drought affected population at the sites of origin. The mobile health teams will also provide health and basic hygiene education sessions using the standard IEC developed by the MoPH. 

In addition, the proposed health teams will be mobilized to strengthen referral systems by promoting public awareness and providing the transportation for delivery and obstetric complications to the higher level of HFs (the MHT vehicles will transport the patients whenever needed).</narrative>
  </description>
